import java.util.*;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String s = "programming";

        // LinkedHashMap preserves insertion order
        Map<Character, Integer> map = new LinkedHashMap<>();

        // Count frequency
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            map.put(c, map.getOrDefault(c, 0) + 1);
        }

        // Print duplicates in order of appearance
        System.out.print("Duplicate characters: ");
        for (Map.Entry<Character, Integer> entry : map.entrySet()) {
            if (entry.getValue() > 1) {
                System.out.print(entry.getKey() + " ");
            }
        }
    }
}

‚è± Complexity

Time: O(n) ‚Üí traverse string once

Space: O(n) ‚Üí store unique characters

üé§ How to Explain in Interview

‚ÄúI use LinkedHashMap to count character frequencies and maintain insertion order.
Then I print only characters with frequency > 1.
This is optimal and clean, runs in linear time, and keeps output in original order.‚Äù

üî• Follow-Up Questions Interviewers May Ask

Can you do it without extra space?

Only if character set is fixed (like lowercase a-z) using array of size 26.

What if case-insensitive?

Convert string to lowercase first.

What if you want most repeated character?

Track maxFreq while building map.
